summarization.results: In the 6th century, power shifted from Rome to Constantinople due to barbarian invasions. Emperor Justinian's rise in Constantinople and his relationship with Theodora influenced political maneuverings in Rome. Theodora played a role in manipulating the election of Pope Vigilius, marking a transition in power dynamics. Despite controversies and power struggles, Pope Vigilius, once an anti-pope, became a real pope in 538 after a conversion. He endured 17 years of imprisonment under Theodora and Justinian, remaining steadfast in his faith. His story reflects a moment of grace in a challenging time for the Church.
